Decide which of the following sets (with the natural addition and scalar multiplication) are vector spaces. Justify your answer.

1) The set of all continuous functions on the interval $[0,1]$;

2) The set of all non-negative functions on $[0,1]$;

3) The set of all polynomials of degree exactly $n$;

4) The set of all symmetric $n\times n$ matrices, i.e. matrices $A=\{a_{j,k}\}_{j,k=1}^n$ such that $A^T=A$.

Determine whether each statement is true or false:

1) Every vector space contains a zero vector;

2) A vector space can have more than one zero vector;

3) An $m\times n$ matrix has $m$ rows and $n$ columns;

4) If $f$ and $g$ are polynomials of degree $n$, then $f+g$ is also degree $n$;

5) If $f$ and $g$ are polynomials of degree at most $n$, then $f+g$ has degree at most $n$.
